WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:25.730 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: Good afternoon.

00:00:25.730 --> 00:00:28.310
I'm Paul Fraunfelter
with the Music Division.

00:00:28.310 --> 00:00:34.000
And I call this presentation, World
War One Sheet Music at the Library

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.870 position:56%
of Congress, America's War as
Viewed by Publishers and the Public.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.300
So, 100 years ago today,
Congress was

00:00:44.300 --> 00:00:48.520
across the street debating
President Wilson's war resolution.

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:52.600
And very soon, songs like the
hit, "I Didn't Raise My Boy

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:56.670 position:56%
to Be a Soldier," and the
"Neutrality Rag," would no longer be

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:58.770
in the national interest.

00:00:58.770 --> 00:01:02.420
During the period of
neutrality, anger at Germany

00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:06.540
and sympathy towards France and
Britain, had steadily increased.

00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:12.010
Yet, when the War Declaration came,
there was little public interest

00:01:12.010 --> 00:01:14.530
or enthusiasm to actively join

00:01:14.530 --> 00:01:18.400
in with what was then
called the European War.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.290
In order to gain support
for the war effort

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:24.420
and help spread the
national message,

00:01:24.420 --> 00:01:28.970
President Wilson established the
Committee on Public Information.

00:01:28.970 --> 00:01:34.750
The CPI was the official
government propaganda instrument.

00:01:34.750 --> 00:01:39.980
And very quickly, their
activities became widespread

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:43.190
and pervasive in American life.

00:01:43.190 --> 00:01:50.680
Only around for two years, CPI
quickly expanded from propaganda.

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:52.820
Got into censorship.

00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:57.420
Attempted to control all war
news that reached the public.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:02.790
And even engaged in public
attacks on groups or individuals

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:08.160
that it felt were less
than 100% American.

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:13.490
Today, the CPI is usually
remembered for two things.

00:02:13.490 --> 00:02:17.830
The posters it commissioned
and the work of its film unit.

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:22.940 position:56%
The picture you see up here, the
image, is -- that covers both basis.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:28.860
This is a poster about
one of their movies there,

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:32.340
one of their two feature
films that they had.

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:35.540
It's also an example of what
you can find in the prints

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:39.350
and photographs division,
online World War One posters.

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:41.720
There's a lot of cool stuff there.

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:44.160
I love going there.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:47.790
But for the ability to
reach a mass audience,

00:02:47.790 --> 00:02:50.590
in a time before mass
communications,

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:55.820
probably their most effective
initiative was the Speaker series.

00:02:55.820 --> 00:03:04.760 position:56%
CPI sponsored programs that featured
patriotic, often inflammatory

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:09.570
or incendiary speeches,
given by Four Minute Men.

00:03:09.570 --> 00:03:12.230
So called for the length
of these addresses.

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:18.970
And this really was a
saturation campaign.

00:03:18.970 --> 00:03:24.530
These meetings kind of took
like a town hall sort of format.

00:03:24.530 --> 00:03:27.810
Any place they could get
a room, you know, schools,

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:30.490
churches, maybe libraries.

00:03:30.490 --> 00:03:34.440
Every village, every town,
any place they could get in.

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.350
By the end of the war, over 750,000

00:03:37.350 --> 00:03:40.930
of these speeches had
been given nationwide.

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:43.880
The programs also finished --

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:47.540
finished, well, maybe they
finished with it, maybe not.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:52.080
But they also included
patriotic group singing.

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:54.860
Similarly called Four
Minute Singing.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:58.220 position:56%
And this is also another CPI poster.

00:03:58.220 --> 00:04:01.850
And note the blank
space at the bottom,

00:04:01.850 --> 00:04:04.910
where local printers
could put venue and date

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:10.800
and time information
for upcoming shows.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:17.310
So, with the war, now foremost in
the public's mind, the songwriters

00:04:17.310 --> 00:04:21.600
of New York Cities, Tin Pan Alley,
the music publishing district,

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:25.450
now began producing work
reflective of the new reality.

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:29.780
In 1917, the Vaudeville
Variety Stage,

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:33.840
was the nation's chief source
of public entertainment.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:36.580
And the cinema, of
course, was still silent.

00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:40.260 position:56%
It had not overtaken Vaudeville yet.

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:46.540 position:56%
Recording was important, but at that
time, considered a secondary market.

00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:51.710
And of course, broadcast radio
was several years in the future.

00:04:51.710 --> 00:04:57.340
The publishers promoted their
songs to the Vaudeville performers

00:04:57.340 --> 00:05:01.610
or their agents, to get
them to perform the songs.

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:04.620
Present them to the public
on the Vaudeville circuit.

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:09.030
Hopefully make hits, which would
drive demand for the sheet music.

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:13.230
Sheet music sales was the
publishers chief source

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:14.780
of income, at that time.

00:05:14.780 --> 00:05:20.040
And this was still, you know,
very much the era of the piano

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:23.330
in the parlor and making
your own music at home.

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:31.240
In 2013, the music division,
catalogued and scanned

00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:36.680
about 14,000 pieces of World
War One classified sheet music.

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:40.500
As you can see in the breakdown,
about 80% of it's printed.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:43.220
About 20% of it is manuscript.

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:49.470
From the printed, there's a 60, 40
split between for profit commercial

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:54.270
and self-published and
amateur vanity press.

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:57.570
The manuscripts are essentially
all copyright deposits.

00:05:57.570 --> 00:06:01.130
But within that, it's
kind of a mix bag

00:06:01.130 --> 00:06:03.850
of what they may have
been when they came in.

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:08.010
There are pieces that
are obviously the work

00:06:08.010 --> 00:06:12.280
of an experienced musician
or a copyist.

00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:16.440
There's some really rough stuff
that's obviously amateur work.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:19.830
And there's even more
gray area in-between.

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:24.410
Where it's hard to determine
where that may have come from.

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:26.200
There's also a good chunk

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:29.890
of non-print manuscript
vanity press pieces.

00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:34.430
But I'd say probably
about 35 to 40% of it.

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:38.190
We have well over 1,2000
pieces in there.

00:06:38.190 --> 00:06:43.190
And there are also manuscript
drafts that were sent

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:48.140
in for copyright deposit, prior
to subsequent publication.

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:52.860
If you dig around in the website
long enough and you look around,

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:56.290
you'll realize that
there are many songs

00:06:56.290 --> 00:07:00.710
that we have both the
copyright deposit manuscript

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:03.760
and the first printed edition.

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:10.590
So, overall, what we have in
the collection, is a collection

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:14.630
that was created by
publishers and the public.

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:19.820
I want to talk a little
bit about the Vanity Press.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:23.470
The column that you see here,

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:29.740
is a detail from the sheet
music websites display list.

00:07:29.740 --> 00:07:34.070
And the top nine entries,
the most prolific producers

00:07:34.070 --> 00:07:36.320
of World War One songs,

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:42.090
are all either Vanity Press
song writers or publishers.

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:45.880
There's a little intersection
in the numbers here.

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:49.060
You see Leo Friedman and North
American Music are very close.

00:07:49.060 --> 00:07:54.510
Well, Leo Friedman was associated
with North American Music.

00:07:54.510 --> 00:08:00.660
Similarly, Hector Richard here,
was associated with Legters.

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:05.790
Also, not all these song
writers worked exclusively

00:08:05.790 --> 00:08:07.500
for the Vanity Press.

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:10.350
Or at least some point
of the careers,

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:13.400
they did freelance or outside work.

00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:15.710
Leo Friedman had a hit.

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:19.150
He wrote the music for "Let
Me Call You Sweetheart."

00:08:19.150 --> 00:08:21.970
And George Graff, down
here, wrote the music

00:08:21.970 --> 00:08:25.110
for "When Irish Eyes are Smiling."

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:32.340
The basic agreement was
that someone with a poem,

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:35.730
usually an original poem,
that they wanted set

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:38.250
to music, to make a song of.

00:08:38.250 --> 00:08:43.440
Would contact a Vanity Press and
pay them to have their song writer

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:47.980
or pulper, as they were known,
to set the song to music.

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:53.390
And the Vanity Press would
take care of copyright deposit.

00:08:53.390 --> 00:08:56.920
Beyond that, there are two
different business models found

00:08:56.920 --> 00:08:58.380
in the collection.

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:03.830
The first is that the client
would then choose from a selection

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:07.240
of standard cover illustrations.

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:08.540
Here you see four.

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:10.550
There were about 16
in the collection

00:09:10.550 --> 00:09:13.450
that you see over and over again.

00:09:13.450 --> 00:09:18.210
With just the title
and the names changed.

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:24.180
The agreed upon issue would then
be printed out on cheap stock

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:27.770
in a standard piano
vocal arrangement.

00:09:27.770 --> 00:09:32.040
Two versus and a chorus, is
what the client usually got.

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:37.440
Then the whole thing was delivered
to the client, to distribute

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:40.090
or market, if they wished.

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:43.620
However, they wanted to do that.

00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:51.120
The other model, according to the
account of someone who had worked

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:54.660
for one of these people as a
copyist during the depression,

00:09:54.660 --> 00:09:59.060
was that the Vanity
Press sold the client

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:02.510
on the dream of fame and fortune.

00:10:02.510 --> 00:10:06.340
By promising to promote their song

00:10:06.340 --> 00:10:10.060
to a large commercial
publishing house.

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:12.620
You know, hopefully get it
on the Vaudeville circuit

00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:17.930
and become a hit and
fame and fortune.

00:10:17.930 --> 00:10:22.200
This is a piece by Raymond Brown.

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:27.060
And he was the most prolific
pulper in this business model.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:31.120
We have over 740 of his pieces.

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:34.640
And I find his stuff
a little unusual

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:37.860
because he would always break
his songs down into components.

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:42.580 position:56%
He would identify the
introduction, the verse, the chorus.

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:46.640
And then put the client's
lyrics pasted directly

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:49.150
onto the main script sheet.

00:10:49.150 --> 00:10:52.230
Notice that it is just the melody.

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:54.110
There's no harmonization.

00:10:54.110 --> 00:10:56.940
There's no arrangement.

00:10:56.940 --> 00:11:01.090
This is also kind of
uncharacteristic for one

00:11:01.090 --> 00:11:03.230
of Brown's pieces because
of its length.

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:07.600
He's got a 24-bar verse
and a 16-bar chorus.

00:11:07.600 --> 00:11:12.080
Some of his pieces in there are
as simple as a four-bar intro,

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:16.470
an eight-bar verse and
an eight-bar chorus.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:22.790
Other pulpers that worked in this
business model, delivered something

00:11:22.790 --> 00:11:24.900
that looked a lot like Brown's.

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:29.550
But they would write the verse
chorus sequence out in something

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:34.770
that closely resembles
a modern lead sheet.

00:11:34.770 --> 00:11:39.510
The finished product
was three copies.

00:11:39.510 --> 00:11:42.270
The client, of course,
would get one.

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:48.220
The Vanity Press would keep one,
supposedly to show to publishers.

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:51.780
And the Library of
Congress got the third.

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:57.130
And the copyist, I mentioned
before, said in her time

00:11:57.130 --> 00:12:02.990
with the Vanity Press, she had seen
her boss attempt to sell one piece

00:12:02.990 --> 00:12:06.980
of music to a publishing house.

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:13.190
So, now let's get to the meat
and potatoes of the collection.

00:12:13.190 --> 00:12:18.410
And look at some of the
recurring themes and subjects.

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:20.750
Why were we at war?

00:12:20.750 --> 00:12:24.240
Well, there were a whole
lot of contributing factors.

00:12:24.240 --> 00:12:28.300
But of course, the straw that broke
the camel's back was Germanies

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:31.250
declaration of unrestricted
submarine warfare.

00:12:31.250 --> 00:12:38.130
The U-boat songs in the collection,
typically do not depict U-boats

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:42.410
as menaces or high seas killers.

00:12:42.410 --> 00:12:46.730
But more like nuisances, which
we'll quickly dispense of.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:49.390
We'll sweep them from the seas.

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:55.450 position:56%
And in many of these songs, there is
a demeaning superior attitude shown

00:12:55.450 --> 00:12:56.750
towards the enemy.

00:12:56.750 --> 00:12:59.980
And that attitude --
that's why I put this first,

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:04.480
carries over throughout
the collection.

00:13:04.480 --> 00:13:07.920
President Wilson's
famous declaration,

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:11.870
"The world must be made
safe for democracy."

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:15.660
Actually, got him some
heat in Congress

00:13:15.660 --> 00:13:20.790
for inserting ideology
into the war resolution.

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:23.570
But it resounded with the public.

00:13:23.570 --> 00:13:29.410
There are songs about democracy,
the defense of democracy.

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:32.280
The triumph of democracy
and the doom

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:35.550
of the militaristic
German autocracy.

00:13:35.550 --> 00:13:39.940
And I said this resounded with
the public, as the majority

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:43.150
of these kinds of songs all
come from the Vanity Press

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:46.090
and the manuscripts deposits.

00:13:46.090 --> 00:13:54.250
The enemy was often characterized
or embodied in Kaiser Wilhelm.

00:13:54.250 --> 00:14:00.280
He's shown as the chief provocateur
and a villain of the war.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:02.140
Old Satan gets the [inaudible],

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:07.270
as a very typically cover
treatment of Wilhelm.

00:14:07.270 --> 00:14:11.720
He's shown several times with
the devil or with other demons.

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:14.870
But he can be chased by goats.

00:14:14.870 --> 00:14:19.250
He can be tomahawked by a
gigantic American Indian.

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:24.650
He can be thrown in a prison van by
a laughing John Bull and Uncle Sam.

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:28.480
And those variations go on.

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:32.940
The Bleeding Belgium Campaign,
was an appeal of sympathy

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:39.370
that brought Britain its first
wave of volunteers in 1914.

00:14:39.370 --> 00:14:47.960 position:56%
And though there a few Belgium songs
in the collection, prior to 1917,

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:53.150
the amount of songs about German
atrocities in Belgium that appear

00:14:53.150 --> 00:14:57.540
in 1917, suggests that
when we entered the war,

00:14:57.540 --> 00:15:01.590
we too took up the
Bleeding Belgium campaign.

00:15:01.590 --> 00:15:07.830
If there's one thing the common
person, just about everybody knows

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:12.480
about World War One in
America, is that the invocation

00:15:12.480 --> 00:15:16.380
of the Great Revolutionary War
hero, the Marquis de Lafayette,

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:22.570
was a powerful, popular,
emotional appeal at that time.

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:27.260
And there are, indeed,
songs reminding the listener

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:32.210 position:56%
that it was now Lafayette's homeland
that was facing its dark hour.

00:15:32.210 --> 00:15:34.960
And we had an old debt to repay.

00:15:39.690 --> 00:15:46.550
When we entered the war,
literally, we did not have a plan.

00:15:46.550 --> 00:15:51.260
Certainly, we knew that our money
and our Navy would be involved.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:56.660
But as to if we were going to
commit troops and what level

00:15:56.660 --> 00:15:59.150
of that commitment would
be, was still unknown.

00:15:59.150 --> 00:16:06.050
And certainly, no one in
Washington here, in April,1917,

00:16:06.050 --> 00:16:12.920 position:56%
thought we were going to send troops
to Europe and rescue the allies.

00:16:12.920 --> 00:16:17.000
However, there's always a however.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:21.460
The day after war was
declared, George M. Cohan,

00:16:21.460 --> 00:16:23.980 position:56%
who was already a popular songwriter

00:16:23.980 --> 00:16:27.690
and Broadway producer,
wrote, "Over There."

00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:31.820
And three weeks later,
when he presented it

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:34.730
to the public, it was
an instant hit.

00:16:34.730 --> 00:16:37.910
And was one of the driving forces

00:16:37.910 --> 00:16:43.440
of creating the idea
of the Grand Crusade.

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:47.240
In 1909, the U.S. became
the world's largest economy.

00:16:47.240 --> 00:16:49.680
In 1914, a lending nation.

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:57.280 position:56%
And entering the war, solidified
America's position as a world power.

00:16:57.280 --> 00:17:05.100
Cover illustrations of songs about
the alliance, often relay a message

00:17:05.100 --> 00:17:10.230
of equality with the traditional
powers, France and Britain.

00:17:10.230 --> 00:17:12.820
Usually you see the
three flags together.

00:17:12.820 --> 00:17:15.880
The U.S. flag is always
front and center.

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:19.480
Sometimes you'll see
Pershing and his counterparts

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:23.240 position:56%
or even Wilson and his counterparts.

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:29.990
This is also the first time we sent
large numbers of troops overseas.

00:17:29.990 --> 00:17:34.460
And there's a body of mostly
self-deprecating songs

00:17:34.460 --> 00:17:39.100
about young American's
experiences with French culture

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:42.520
and French language
and French women.

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:46.430
The most enduring of these
songs, actually comes

00:17:46.430 --> 00:17:48.180
from the post-war period.

00:17:48.180 --> 00:17:49.980
And the name of that song is?

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:52.490
[ Inaudible Answers ]

00:17:52.490 --> 00:17:55.910
"How Ya Gonna Keep'em Down on The
Farm, After They've Seen Paree?"

00:17:55.910 --> 00:17:59.560
Exactly. But we did
not come empty handed.

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:04.130
We brought with us, arguably,
the greatest cultural export

00:18:04.130 --> 00:18:08.000
of the twentieth century and jazz.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:14.790
And there are, indeed, early
jazz songs in the collection.

00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:22.030
And for those inclined to want to
go looking for them, I think I need

00:18:22.030 --> 00:18:25.480
to offer some sort
of kind of a caveat.

00:18:25.480 --> 00:18:31.500
You know, today, we have
well, clearly defined genres.

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:34.070
Back then, not so much.

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:36.980
And when you're working
in a collection

00:18:36.980 --> 00:18:42.900
and you see the terms
ragtime, blues and jazz,

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:48.660
keep in mind that they used those
terms pretty interchangeably.

00:18:48.660 --> 00:18:51.630
There are also songs about jazz.

00:18:51.630 --> 00:18:54.810
And these normally
follow a narrative

00:18:54.810 --> 00:18:57.970
of the young Americans
on their way in Europe.

00:18:57.970 --> 00:19:02.030
And they're eagerly anticipating
what the European reception

00:19:02.030 --> 00:19:06.320
to jazz is going to be.

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:12.860
The mantra or motto of the
day, was 100% American.

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:17.920
And that came, not from the
CPI, but from a still active

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:21.310
and very vocal former
President Theodore Roosevelt,

00:19:21.310 --> 00:19:23.830
during the run up to the war.

00:19:23.830 --> 00:19:29.040
Songs of general appeal, have names
like, "We're All Comrades Now."

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:31.080
"We're All True Americans."

00:19:31.080 --> 00:19:33.460
"We're All in the Same Boat Now."

00:19:33.460 --> 00:19:37.540 position:56%
And "There's no Hyphen in My Heart."

00:19:39.620 --> 00:19:44.140
There are songs by,
about or directed to,

00:19:44.140 --> 00:19:48.130
most every ethnic group present
in the country, at the time.

00:19:48.130 --> 00:19:52.930
But the numbers favor
three groups in particular.

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:58.310
For African Americans, this
was a time of flux and change.

00:19:58.310 --> 00:20:00.820
The Great Migration
from the rural south

00:20:00.820 --> 00:20:03.850
to the industrial north,
was underway.

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:06.330
The NAACP had been founded.

00:20:06.330 --> 00:20:11.030
And the Modern Civil Rights
Movement, is rooted in as time.

00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:15.360
African American song writers
were active in Tin Pan Alley.

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:19.790
African Americans, of course,
were the driving force in jazz.

00:20:19.790 --> 00:20:26.890
African Americans now had influence
in mainstream American culture.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:29.500
Irish Americans, then, as now,

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:33.030
were one of the two largest ethnic
groups present in the country.

00:20:33.030 --> 00:20:36.770
And historically, their
participation

00:20:36.770 --> 00:20:40.370
in the American military
has been critical.

00:20:40.370 --> 00:20:44.170
But at that time, there
was unrest in Ireland.

00:20:44.170 --> 00:20:47.450
And a degree of anti-British
sentiment

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:52.470
in the Irish American communities
here, that had to be addressed.

00:20:52.470 --> 00:20:55.830
Italian Americans were
the newcomers.

00:20:55.830 --> 00:21:01.570
Between 1880 and 1920, about
four million Italians immigrated

00:21:01.570 --> 00:21:06.620
to the U.S. Most in the
decade before the war.

00:21:06.620 --> 00:21:12.260 position:56%
And the songs of serious or
earnest appeal to Italian Americans,

00:21:12.260 --> 00:21:16.650
differ in that most are
not calls for volunteers.

00:21:16.650 --> 00:21:23.020
But rather, songs in support
of the European Italian allies.

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:27.310
And what of my people?

00:21:27.310 --> 00:21:31.290
The other of the two
largest ethnic groups?

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:34.570
Well, you'll find a lot of
German names in the collection.

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:39.040
They're all song writers
and publishers.

00:21:39.040 --> 00:21:43.990
I found two songs,
manuscript deposits,

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:47.780
about patriotic German Americans.

00:21:47.780 --> 00:21:54.840
We must remember that ethnic
comedy was a staple component

00:21:54.840 --> 00:21:57.540
of the Vaudeville stage.

00:21:57.540 --> 00:22:02.670
And for every one heartfelt
earnest appeal made

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:08.570
to any particular ethnic group,
there are multiple songs directed

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:15.300
to that same ethnic group that mock
appearance, accents and customs.

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:20.290
Ironically, even the stereotype
stuff is couched in terms

00:22:20.290 --> 00:22:24.940
to serve unity and the war effort.

00:22:24.940 --> 00:22:29.110
The Civil War had been
over for a scant 50 years.

00:22:29.110 --> 00:22:32.710
And the grandsons of the
Confederacy, were expected to fight

00:22:32.710 --> 00:22:35.970
and die for the Federal Government.

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:39.670
Appeals had to be made to the
still disenfranchised south.

00:22:39.670 --> 00:22:44.310
There are Civil War reunion songs,
"Boys of the Blue and the Gray,"

00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:47.130
"Sons of the Blue and the Gray."

00:22:47.130 --> 00:22:52.120
"Dixie Land" and "Yankee Doodle
Land," are one in the same today.

00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:58.270
There are also songs about
or directed to the south.

00:22:58.270 --> 00:23:02.590
All you really need to
do is get to the site.

00:23:02.590 --> 00:23:10.790
And in the search box, type in the
word Dixie and see what you get.

00:23:10.790 --> 00:23:14.270
Unsurprisingly, the bulk
of the collection though,

00:23:14.270 --> 00:23:19.840
is given to the traditional
wartime topics, patriotism,

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:21.900
home and hearth and women.

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:27.820
The patriotic stuff is pretty much
what you would expect, my homeland,

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:31.550
my nation, my flag, my president.

00:23:31.550 --> 00:23:38.280
But there are some topics in there
that are historically important

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:42.670
or has a -- I'll keep it at that.

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:47.900
Uncle Sam, the characterization
or the personification

00:23:47.900 --> 00:23:50.130
of the U.S. Government, had been

00:23:50.130 --> 00:23:52.590
around since the early
nineteenth century.

00:23:52.590 --> 00:23:55.980
But his appearances were sporadic.

00:23:55.980 --> 00:23:58.450
His physical appearance
could change.

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:00.310
His name could be different.

00:24:00.310 --> 00:24:04.940
It was not until here, in
World War One, that the tall,

00:24:04.940 --> 00:24:09.390
goateed man in the red, white
and blue suit, became universal.

00:24:09.390 --> 00:24:13.450
And if this collection has
a star, it's Uncle Sam.

00:24:13.450 --> 00:24:17.800
And in titles, cover illustrations,

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:22.690
song content, lyrics,
he's everywhere.

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:27.470
The use of the service flag
is a tradition that began

00:24:27.470 --> 00:24:31.290
in World War One and
continues to this day.

00:24:31.290 --> 00:24:35.050
When a family member in
the military is deployed,

00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:39.330
the family is issued a
small flag or banner,

00:24:39.330 --> 00:24:41.990
bearing a blue star for
that service member.

00:24:41.990 --> 00:24:46.220
Here you see one in
this window here.

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:49.830
Particularly during World War Two,
it was not uncommon to see flags

00:24:49.830 --> 00:24:52.960
with two, three, four
stars, for however many

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:55.330
that household were serving.

00:24:55.330 --> 00:24:58.640
If the member is killed in action,

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:02.300
the blue star is replaced
by a gold star.

00:25:02.300 --> 00:25:07.120
And there's songs about service
flags, blue stars, gold stars.

00:25:07.120 --> 00:25:09.920
And when the blue star
turns to gold.

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:15.430
And these songs seem to be evenly
divided between the commercial

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:19.200
and the amateur song writers.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:24.050
At that time, the traditional
roles of women still prevailed.

00:25:24.050 --> 00:25:28.570
We have wives, we have patient,
sympathetic sweethearts.

00:25:28.570 --> 00:25:32.650
And first and foremost, centrally

00:25:32.650 --> 00:25:37.060
and most important,
there are mothers.

00:25:37.060 --> 00:25:43.440
In cover illustrations, it's not
unusual to find female architypes.

00:25:43.440 --> 00:25:48.890
You know, often with the long
clarion horn or the sword,

00:25:48.890 --> 00:25:51.730
rallying the boys,
calling to the boys.

00:25:51.730 --> 00:25:53.580
Leading to the boys.

00:25:53.580 --> 00:25:57.270
There's Columbia, there's liberty.

00:25:57.270 --> 00:26:04.020
There are generic noble looking
women in Greek and Roman dress.

00:26:04.020 --> 00:26:08.310
And of course, as we
were going to France,

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:12.150
Joan of Arc makes her appearances.

00:26:12.150 --> 00:26:16.330
When it comes to women's war
work, there's a slight schism

00:26:16.330 --> 00:26:19.580
between the commercial
and the amateur pieces.

00:26:19.580 --> 00:26:25.280
The commercial pieces are almost
solely given to two occupations.

00:26:25.280 --> 00:26:28.450
The nurse, in particular,
the Red Cross nurse,

00:26:28.450 --> 00:26:31.080
as opposed to the military nurses.

00:26:31.080 --> 00:26:34.850
And the Salvation Army girls,
who dispense coffee and donuts

00:26:34.850 --> 00:26:37.810
and cakes, near the front.

00:26:37.810 --> 00:26:40.550
Again, cover illustrations.

00:26:40.550 --> 00:26:47.070 position:56%
Sometimes you can see women in other
war work, carrying hose or spades

00:26:47.070 --> 00:26:51.380
or maybe driving a truck or
maybe working in a factory.

00:26:51.380 --> 00:26:53.640
But the songs themselves, don't go

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:58.670
into any great detail
about this work.

00:26:58.670 --> 00:27:03.860
The amateur songs, also
skew heavily towards nurses

00:27:03.860 --> 00:27:06.320
and Salvation Army girls.

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:09.170
But here you can find songs

00:27:09.170 --> 00:27:14.690
about particular women's
wartime occupations.

00:27:14.690 --> 00:27:18.410
Like, the operation of
the Women's Land Army,

00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:21.540
that replaced agricultural
workers gone to war.

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:26.310
And the conductorettes that
worked on the railroads.

00:27:29.500 --> 00:27:33.420
How does the collections
treatment of these themes,

00:27:33.420 --> 00:27:38.760
compare with the CPI's agenda?

00:27:38.760 --> 00:27:43.260
Overall, content of the
commercially published pieces,

00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:47.980
is consistent with the
national message of the time.

00:27:47.980 --> 00:27:54.140 position:56%
Public reception, if we can judge it

00:27:54.140 --> 00:27:57.800
from the amateur pieces,
was positive.

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:03.810
As the vast majority of these
things mime what Tin Pan Alley

00:28:03.810 --> 00:28:05.760
was producing.

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:07.570
That's not to say that
everything fits

00:28:07.570 --> 00:28:10.190
into a nice big mainstream package.

00:28:10.190 --> 00:28:14.360
Outside the larger
better represented themes,

00:28:14.360 --> 00:28:17.780
there are smaller groups
or individual songs.

00:28:17.780 --> 00:28:23.650
Which are also reflective of
American society at the time.

00:28:23.650 --> 00:28:29.450
And an ethnic group, I hadn't
mentioned earlier, was Eastern

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:33.960
and Central Europeans who
came here in the millions,

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:37.030
at the same time the Italians came.

00:28:37.030 --> 00:28:42.600
We can find Polish Freedom Fighter
songs, calling for Polish Americans

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:47.300
to go back to the homeland
and free it from the Russians.

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:50.670
And the Austrians and the Germans.

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:52.980
There are Zionist songs.

00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:55.840
There are anti-Bolshevist songs.

00:28:55.840 --> 00:28:58.130
Some of them calling
for intervention

00:28:58.130 --> 00:29:01.270
in the Russian Revolution.

00:29:01.270 --> 00:29:05.600
The largest group of a war
related special interest songs,

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:10.840
are songs in support of Wilson's
Internationalists Agenda, i.e.

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:13.420
; the Foundation of
the League of Nations.

00:29:13.420 --> 00:29:16.250
But you know, you can
also find the other camp.

00:29:16.250 --> 00:29:21.040
You can find more nationalistic
songs that would appeal to people

00:29:21.040 --> 00:29:27.470
like the National Security League
and Teddy Roosevelt's followers.

00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:33.340
The U.S. did not impose food
rationing, during World War One.

00:29:33.340 --> 00:29:36.300
But a Federal Agency,
was established

00:29:36.300 --> 00:29:40.640
that encourage people
to economize on food.

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:44.980
And looked into things like
better food distribution.

00:29:44.980 --> 00:29:53.190 position:56%
There is, to me, a surprising amount
of songs devoted to this initiative.

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:57.170
And to the food administrations
rising political star,

00:29:57.170 --> 00:29:59.750
Herbert Hoover.

00:29:59.750 --> 00:30:02.050
There are, of course,
war bond songs.

00:30:02.050 --> 00:30:09.140
And a curious little group of
amateur songs about Pershing's,

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:13.140
1916 Mexican exertion or incursion.

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:18.290
That's the one where he failed
to capture or kill Pancho Villa.

00:30:18.290 --> 00:30:22.850
And these songs all promise
that Black Jack is coming home.

00:30:22.850 --> 00:30:26.980
And he's going to take care of
unfinished business down there.

00:30:28.060 --> 00:30:34.710
And it seems that the -- no sooner
was the ink dry on the armistice,

00:30:34.710 --> 00:30:38.830
that some of the disillusionment
and cynicism

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:43.100
that post-war period was
known for, starts creeping

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:46.260
into some of the song lyrics.

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:50.360
Probably the easiest place
to spot them is songs

00:30:50.360 --> 00:30:52.860
about Veterans returning home,

00:30:52.860 --> 00:30:57.120
looking for work, often
unsuccessfully.

00:30:57.120 --> 00:31:01.860
There's even one song called, "Why
Shouldn't They Be Good Enough Now."

00:31:01.860 --> 00:31:07.790
Which is about women war workers
resisting pressure to return

00:31:07.790 --> 00:31:12.410
to domesticity, to make
room for the males.

00:31:12.410 --> 00:31:18.350
Another post-war hot topic
was the impending ratification

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:21.560
of the Eighteenth Amendment,
the Prohibition Amendment.

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:27.490 position:56%
And based on the songs, I don't know
how that thing ever got ratified.

00:31:27.490 --> 00:31:30.630
It was not popular.

00:31:30.630 --> 00:31:33.940
There are some pro-temperance
songs in there,

00:31:33.940 --> 00:31:37.840
but they are a decided minority.

00:31:37.840 --> 00:31:45.690
And then we get to my favorites,
which is the occasional piece

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:50.370
that displays a personal
view or an opinion

00:31:50.370 --> 00:31:54.690
or may even relate an experience.

00:31:54.690 --> 00:31:58.490
Something I noticed, while
working with the collection,

00:31:58.490 --> 00:32:03.720
was that socially conscious songs,
like the one I just mentioned.

00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:07.570
And are they equal, in
the eyes of the law?

00:32:07.570 --> 00:32:12.400
All are self-published.

00:32:12.400 --> 00:32:16.480
I'll let y'all draw your
own conclusions about that.

00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:19.680
There is a manuscript called

00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:24.330
"What Price Has Pershing
Paid for Dead Man's Hill?"

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:29.810
Which takes issue with
casualties sustained during part

00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:32.260
of the [inaudible] campaign.

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:35.880
There is another manuscript
called "Heaven."

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:41.430
Which was written for
the composer's sister,

00:32:41.430 --> 00:32:44.050
who was nurse that
died during the war,

00:32:44.050 --> 00:32:46.660
that was killed during
the war, actually.

00:32:46.660 --> 00:32:52.970
And it's the only mention I found
in the collection that young women

00:32:52.970 --> 00:32:57.140
who served near the front,
could also be casualties.

00:32:58.400 --> 00:33:01.990 position:56%
And then we have, "A Soldiers Wife,"

00:33:01.990 --> 00:33:05.180
which is basically a
hum and hearth song.

00:33:05.180 --> 00:33:11.340
Which tells the tale of soldier
who dutifully sends home his pay,

00:33:11.340 --> 00:33:15.760
only to find that his wife had
spent it all on another man.

00:33:15.760 --> 00:33:19.350
And this is personal favorite
of mine, as it's local.

00:33:19.350 --> 00:33:24.330
It's by Mrs. Carrie Baker of
Martinsburg, West Virginia.

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:26.710
And one can only speculate

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:31.810
on what Mrs. Baker's
inspiration for this song was.

00:33:31.810 --> 00:33:33.110
So, there you have it.

00:33:33.110 --> 00:33:36.870
That's the grand tour,
the big overview.

00:33:36.870 --> 00:33:39.070
I pointed out some
of the highlights.

00:33:39.070 --> 00:33:45.880
But again, with almost
14,000 pieces up online,

00:33:45.880 --> 00:33:49.050
there is just so much to explore.

00:33:49.050 --> 00:33:53.620
A whole lot to discover
in that collection.

00:33:53.620 --> 00:33:56.870
The war notwithstanding,
this was an active

00:33:56.870 --> 00:34:00.260 position:56%
and exciting time in American music.

00:34:00.260 --> 00:34:05.070
I mentioned the development
and the rise of jazz.

00:34:05.070 --> 00:34:08.130
People like Irving
Berlin, Cole Porter,

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:13.140
the teenage George Gershwin,
were young, developing.

00:34:13.140 --> 00:34:18.470
American musical theatre was soon
going to explode, full flower.

00:34:18.470 --> 00:34:21.650
It's probably also
the high-water mark

00:34:21.650 --> 00:34:23.630
of the Vaudeville variety stage,

00:34:23.630 --> 00:34:27.630
before the talkies
and radio took over.

00:34:28.660 --> 00:34:34.890 position:56%
Now, to be honest, I have seen
online, from some other collections,

00:34:34.890 --> 00:34:42.600
a handful of pieces that we
don't have in this collection.

00:34:42.600 --> 00:34:47.920
But that said, this
is still the largest.

00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:52.220
And with the inclusion of the
Vanity Press and manuscripts,

00:34:52.220 --> 00:34:55.410
most comprehensive collection

00:34:55.410 --> 00:35:00.120
of World War One American
sheet music in existence.

00:35:00.120 --> 00:35:06.630
Again, with the Vanity Press and
manuscript stuff, I'm speculating

00:35:06.630 --> 00:35:10.490
that 95% of that stuff
has to be unique.

00:35:10.490 --> 00:35:14.810
Has to be the only
copies left in existence.

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:20.430
There just can't be too many
copies of great grandma's song,

00:35:20.430 --> 00:35:25.800
still floating around out there.

00:35:25.800 --> 00:35:32.620
And finally, sheet music may
not automatically come to mind,

00:35:32.620 --> 00:35:36.780
when looking for historic
source material.

00:35:36.780 --> 00:35:41.420
But remember that these songs
were written by the people

00:35:41.420 --> 00:35:44.080 position:56%
that were experiencing these things,

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:48.110
at the time they were
experiencing them.

00:35:48.110 --> 00:35:51.620
And getting familiar
with this collection,

00:35:51.620 --> 00:35:55.260
may help to develop a
better understanding

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:59.820
of the collective consciousness
of wartime America.

00:35:59.820 --> 00:36:01.620
Thank you.

00:36:01.620 --> 00:36:08.090
[ Applause ]

