I mean, I'm looking at the titles.

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:18.520
And the titles seem to me, to be
the same as the copyrighted music.

00:37:18.520 --> 00:37:19.900
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: Yeah, yeah.

00:37:19.900 --> 00:37:24.470
A lot of -- a lot of just -- a
lot of people just sent it in.

00:37:24.470 --> 00:37:31.040
But well, for the one thing, the
printed Vanity Press, which is,

00:37:31.040 --> 00:37:36.300
you know, the biggest chunk of it,
I mean, your song is printed out.

00:37:36.300 --> 00:37:38.420
It has a publisher's
name on the bottom.

00:37:38.420 --> 00:37:41.920
It has a patriotic
cover on the front.

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:49.330
Plus, Vanity Presses advertised
and the Library of Congress didn't.

00:37:52.090 --> 00:37:54.430
&gt;&gt; Following up, I'm
still a little confused.

00:37:54.430 --> 00:37:57.470
So, is Vanity Press the only --

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:01.350
so, what you're saying is that
there's a group of publishers,

00:38:01.350 --> 00:38:08.060
at the time, who will get a
poetry, set it to music, print it.

00:38:08.060 --> 00:38:10.500
And then they promise their clients

00:38:10.500 --> 00:38:12.720
that they will sell it
to other publishers?

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:14.020
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: No, no.

00:38:14.020 --> 00:38:15.320
&gt;&gt; I'm really sorry.

00:38:15.320 --> 00:38:16.620
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: Yeah.

00:38:16.620 --> 00:38:17.920
There were two different
business models.

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:19.220
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:38:19.220 --> 00:38:23.290 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: One would print
it and then deliver it to the client

00:38:23.290 --> 00:38:25.030
and say, good luck with that.

00:38:25.030 --> 00:38:30.870
Have fun. The other would
take the client's money,

00:38:30.870 --> 00:38:33.160
have their pulper put it to music.

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:34.460
&gt;&gt; Right, okay.

00:38:34.460 --> 00:38:36.560
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: And then
they send them a manuscript copy.

00:38:36.560 --> 00:38:41.110
Now, granted, the copy that we
say there, was in a copyist hand.

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:44.030
So, most of that stuff
is very legible.

00:38:44.030 --> 00:38:46.660
But yeah, the second model,

00:38:46.660 --> 00:38:51.410
the client just got a
manuscript copy of their music.

00:38:51.410 --> 00:38:54.370
And the promise of, you know,
you're going to be famous,

00:38:54.370 --> 00:38:56.510
once I got somebody to
put it on Vaudeville.

00:38:56.510 --> 00:38:58.540
&gt;&gt; And there were a lot of
different companies who did

00:38:58.540 --> 00:39:00.040
that business model,
is what you're saying.

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:03.660
So, the term Vanity Press, really
encompasses a number of companies.

00:39:03.660 --> 00:39:05.430
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: An
inclusive term, yeah.

00:39:05.430 --> 00:39:06.730
&gt;&gt; Okay, okay.

00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:08.030
That was my confusion.

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:09.330
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter:
There were a lot of people

00:39:09.330 --> 00:39:10.630
that practiced in both
business models.

00:39:10.630 --> 00:39:11.930
&gt;&gt; I see, okay.

00:39:11.930 --> 00:39:13.230
I apologize.

00:39:13.230 --> 00:39:14.530
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: No problem.

00:39:14.530 --> 00:39:15.830
&gt;&gt; I wasn't totally clear on that.

00:39:15.830 --> 00:39:18.130
Okay.

00:39:21.700 --> 00:39:25.140
&gt;&gt; Since so much of this industry
was concentrated on one street

00:39:25.140 --> 00:39:27.510
in Manhattan, how much
does all of this --

00:39:27.510 --> 00:39:31.970
what was sent to Vaudevillians,
what was actually recorded

00:39:31.970 --> 00:39:34.140
or what was just shipped
back to the writer?

00:39:34.140 --> 00:39:38.610
How much reflects what Ted Cruz
would call, New York values?

00:39:40.370 --> 00:39:42.470
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter:
New York values.

00:39:42.470 --> 00:39:54.670
I see -- I've seen in the
collection, a lot of, you know,

00:39:54.670 --> 00:39:59.360
old New York Broadway type
of stuff in there, okay?

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:04.580
I don't know what -- I'm sorry,
but I don't pay a whole lot

00:40:04.580 --> 00:40:06.090
of attention to what Ted Cruz says.

00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:08.610
That's me.

00:40:08.610 --> 00:40:10.400
That's not the Library of Congress.

00:40:10.400 --> 00:40:11.810
That's just me.

00:40:11.810 --> 00:40:14.510
So, I don't know what he was
implying with that remark.

00:40:14.510 --> 00:40:32.350
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:40:32.350 --> 00:40:33.650
I don't know.

00:40:33.650 --> 00:40:36.090
You know, I really
wasn't looking for that.

00:40:36.090 --> 00:40:40.710
I mean, you do get -- you
do get a pretty good mix

00:40:40.710 --> 00:40:44.290
of what America was at that time.

00:40:44.290 --> 00:40:51.030
Everybody kind of in here gets a
little exposure, a little chance.

00:40:51.030 --> 00:40:57.660
And you know, the lower
Eastside Jewish experience.

00:40:57.660 --> 00:41:03.480
You know, the have the, what's it
called, the Yiddish Army Blues.

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:05.750
You get songs like that.

00:41:05.750 --> 00:41:07.540
I mean, it's like, you know,

00:41:07.540 --> 00:41:09.900
everybody has a little
piece of the pie here.

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:14.900
It's not, you know,
strictly white bread.

00:41:14.900 --> 00:41:20.030
I mean, you have to figure, too,

00:41:20.030 --> 00:41:26.760
the published stuff here,
was more to entertain.

00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:29.610
It was to entertain and inspire.

00:41:29.610 --> 00:41:36.950
So, the printed stuff was
basically what you see on TV

00:41:36.950 --> 00:41:40.490
and cable today, their
version of that.

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:46.560
So, you know, there is, you
know, a certain view of America.

00:41:46.560 --> 00:41:51.750
But as far as trying to put
like that type of message

00:41:51.750 --> 00:41:54.050
in there, I didn't see it.

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:03.700
&gt;&gt; Had a similar amount of sheet
music been generated during the

00:42:03.700 --> 00:42:09.150
Spanish American War on
public sentiments for that?

00:42:09.150 --> 00:42:12.810 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: I don't know
how many Spanish American War pieces

00:42:12.810 --> 00:42:15.720
there are, to be honest.

00:42:15.720 --> 00:42:18.040
But no, this is the biggest chunk.

00:42:18.040 --> 00:42:26.710 position:56%
Civil War, north and south combined,
are less than 5,000 pieces.

00:42:26.710 --> 00:42:31.340
And that's the next biggest
chunk of war music we have.

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:35.560
&gt;&gt; Did the recorded music
industry also sell sheet music

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:36.860
to go along with their hits?

00:42:36.860 --> 00:42:40.060
Or were those done independently?

00:42:40.060 --> 00:42:44.020
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: That
was done independently.

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:49.680
They bought sheet music
from the publishers.

00:42:49.680 --> 00:42:53.240
And in fact, created libraries.

00:42:53.240 --> 00:42:56.830
We have a collection
here that we think came

00:42:56.830 --> 00:43:02.860
from the old Victor Library or the
Edison Library, Edison sheet music.

00:43:02.860 --> 00:43:06.320
So, yeah, they had --
recording companies

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:12.080
and later radio symphony
orchestras and radio orchestras,

00:43:12.080 --> 00:43:14.490
they had their own music libraries.

00:43:14.490 --> 00:43:19.170
And that was all sheet music
that they published or scores,

00:43:19.170 --> 00:43:24.560
orchestrated scores, in parts
they got from the publishers.

00:43:25.790 --> 00:43:29.740
&gt;&gt; I was wondering, I sensed
that there might be a tension

00:43:29.740 --> 00:43:32.810
between some of the songs
that were emphasizing unity.

00:43:32.810 --> 00:43:34.970
You know, "There's no
Hyphen in My Heart."

00:43:34.970 --> 00:43:36.270
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: Right.

00:43:36.270 --> 00:43:37.610
&gt;&gt; And songs on the other
hand that suggested,

00:43:37.610 --> 00:43:40.730
not necessarily divided loyalties,

00:43:40.730 --> 00:43:43.620
but maybe multiple
loyalties or investments.

00:43:43.620 --> 00:43:48.090 position:56%
As when you talked about the Polish
Freedom Fighters calling for action,

00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:53.030
back in Poland, against
say, Russia or Austria.

00:43:53.030 --> 00:43:57.340
And so, I was curious about
that, to what extent do some

00:43:57.340 --> 00:44:02.600
of the immigrant groups, as well
as groups that by then, of course,

00:44:02.600 --> 00:44:05.800
are deeply rooted in the United
States, such as African Americans.

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:08.860
To what extent do we
see multiple messaging

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:11.650
or multiple loyalties
expressed in these songs?

00:44:11.650 --> 00:44:13.770
So, that people are
actually speaking

00:44:13.770 --> 00:44:16.940
of fights on different fronts?

00:44:16.940 --> 00:44:20.890
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: I know I'm
the poster boy for Vanity Press

00:44:20.890 --> 00:44:22.940
and the manuscript deposits.

00:44:22.940 --> 00:44:29.010
And there is a lot of
bad poetry in there.

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:38.000
But that is really the value
that amateur stuff serves.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:43.190
Because yeah, the -- as I just
said, the published stuff,

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:45.670
the mainstream stuff,
was mainstream.

00:44:45.670 --> 00:44:49.380
It was, you know, general
consumption stuff.

00:44:49.380 --> 00:44:53.490
And you do get into
the amateur stuff.

00:44:53.490 --> 00:44:57.050
And you can see stuff
that is, you know,

00:44:57.050 --> 00:44:59.830
from someone else's point of view.

00:44:59.830 --> 00:45:07.040
Now, again, most people,
like, pretty much ate it up.

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:13.680
The CPI was pretty effective
in selling the war to us.

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:21.240
Because the -- it's pretty
consistent during the war of, like,

00:45:21.240 --> 00:45:23.120
you know, this is my experience.

00:45:23.120 --> 00:45:25.800
But you know, being a
Paul, you know, yeah,

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:27.780
I want to go over there and fight.

00:45:27.780 --> 00:45:30.420
But I want to get, you
know, the damn Russians out.

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:33.520
And those Germans want to take
over and I don't want to let

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:35.700
that happen either, you know.

00:45:35.700 --> 00:45:38.150
But it's, like, the end of the war,

00:45:38.150 --> 00:45:43.060
where you start seeing what
we call today dissention.

00:45:43.060 --> 00:45:45.890
Where, as I said, the
guy goes, like, you know,

00:45:45.890 --> 00:45:50.570
I don't think Pershing
should have, like, you know,

00:45:50.570 --> 00:45:52.970
marched straight into those guns.

00:46:02.430 --> 00:46:03.730
&gt;&gt; Thanks.

00:46:03.730 --> 00:46:05.030
A question about the publishers.

00:46:05.030 --> 00:46:08.590
The published manuscript
sounds like, actually, I mean,

00:46:08.590 --> 00:46:13.520 position:56%
I'm speculating, they actually have
the pulse on what the country wants.

00:46:13.520 --> 00:46:15.880
Because they're publishing
things that they think will sell.

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:20.160
As far as the Vanity
publishing, where would somebody

00:46:20.160 --> 00:46:25.070
like Carrie Baker in Martinsburg,
learn about a Vanity Press?

00:46:25.070 --> 00:46:26.680
Where were they advertising?

00:46:26.680 --> 00:46:29.920
And how were people from all over
the country sending something

00:46:29.920 --> 00:46:31.820
into New York to get
out their songs?

00:46:31.820 --> 00:46:33.120
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter:
They used to advertise

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:34.900
in newspapers and periodicals.

00:46:34.900 --> 00:46:37.790
You know, have your
song set to music.

00:46:37.790 --> 00:46:41.940
But I think it lost.

00:46:41.940 --> 00:46:43.780
I think it flew away
[brief laughter].

00:46:43.780 --> 00:46:46.080
I'm sorry.

00:46:48.180 --> 00:46:51.270
&gt;&gt; Do you have any -- I
know these are copyrights,

00:46:51.270 --> 00:46:53.410
so these are everything
that was submitted.

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:57.670
Do you have any idea
what actually sold?

00:46:57.670 --> 00:47:05.950
And what sort of numbers are we
talking about for the sheet music?

00:47:05.950 --> 00:47:07.310
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter: No, I don't.

00:47:07.310 --> 00:47:09.110
But it's easy enough to find out.

00:47:09.110 --> 00:47:11.970 position:56%
Because we have the trade magazines.

00:47:11.970 --> 00:47:17.780
Just go over to the performing
arts reading room and look it up.

00:47:17.780 --> 00:47:22.200
And I have friends that will help
you do that [brief laughter].

00:47:22.200 --> 00:47:28.570
Yeah. But a lot of the
recognizable hits are in here.

00:47:28.570 --> 00:47:35.760
You know, of course, over there,
Irving Berlin's, you know,

00:47:35.760 --> 00:47:37.820
"How I Hate to Wake
Up in the Morning."

00:47:37.820 --> 00:47:41.740
Which supposedly was
written about his experience

00:47:41.740 --> 00:47:43.270
as a private in the army.

00:47:43.270 --> 00:47:48.320
And so, my grandfather's
favorite song, "K-K-K-Katy."

00:47:48.320 --> 00:47:49.620
He used to sing that.

00:47:49.620 --> 00:47:52.980
He was a World War One vet.

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:56.270
So, yeah, there's quite
a bit of it is popular.

00:47:56.270 --> 00:47:59.330
And there's some titles I
recognized when I went through it.

00:47:59.330 --> 00:48:03.360
But even more, I didn't.

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:07.610
And again, it's just
like anything else it --

00:48:07.610 --> 00:48:12.780
what was popular, is
what the public bought.

00:48:12.780 --> 00:48:15.600
And they did their market research.

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:19.730
And the whole -- I really

00:48:19.730 --> 00:48:25.890
over simplified Tin Pan
Alley's promotion system.

00:48:25.890 --> 00:48:29.150
I mean, the whole thing
about how many pieces

00:48:29.150 --> 00:48:32.170
of sheet music you
print at the first pass.

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:35.480
And they used to have kind of like,
I forget what they called them,

00:48:35.480 --> 00:48:37.920
promotional or like fair copies

00:48:37.920 --> 00:48:40.690
about something they were
thinking about printing.

00:48:40.690 --> 00:48:43.770
But they would just print
like about 1,000 pages first

00:48:43.770 --> 00:48:46.250
and you know, distribute them.

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:49.850
So, I mean, they were market savvy.

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:52.750
Even though it was 100 years
ago, they were market savvy.

00:48:52.750 --> 00:48:57.690
And you're right, I mean, they had
figures and they were keeping track

00:48:57.690 --> 00:48:59.990
of what kind of stuff was selling.

00:49:03.110 --> 00:49:07.120
&gt;&gt; Is there any anti-war
music at all?

00:49:07.120 --> 00:49:11.670
Is there a Pete Seegre of
that generation, a Phil Ochs?

00:49:11.670 --> 00:49:12.970
Or would they not be published?

00:49:12.970 --> 00:49:15.120
How about in the Vanity
Press, do you see any,

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:17.000
we shouldn't be in
this fight, at all?

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:18.580
&gt;&gt; Paul Fraunfelter:
No, just, you know,

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:23.080
just some of the neutrality
stuff in there.

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:25.520 position:56%
Just some neutrality stuff in there.

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:32.400
Again, at the end of the war,

00:49:32.400 --> 00:49:35.200
you start seeing people
second think sometimes.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:40.010
But that all comes from the Vanity
Press, from the copyright deposits.

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:45.800
I've seen nothing in the
commercially published pieces.

00:49:45.800 --> 00:49:49.880
But then again, like I pointed out,

00:49:49.880 --> 00:49:54.760
the potentially controversial
songs, were all self-published.

00:49:54.760 --> 00:50:00.050
So, the, you know, Pete
Seegre got a label here.

00:50:00.050 --> 00:50:03.360
He never would have back then.

00:50:03.360 --> 00:50:07.030
But also, you know,
we have what we have,

00:50:07.030 --> 00:50:11.960
when it comes to the
commercial stuff.

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:15.640
Apparently and I don't know the
provenance of the collection,

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:20.110
but apparently, it was
put together sometime

00:50:20.110 --> 00:50:22.480
after the war, it was assembled.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:27.660
Because there are dates
from like the twenties.

00:50:27.660 --> 00:50:32.430
There are stamps like
from private collections.

00:50:32.430 --> 00:50:36.120
I found a Korean war
song mixed up with them.

00:50:36.120 --> 00:50:40.010
So, the commercial stuff
is, we have what we have.

00:50:40.010 --> 00:50:44.630
But the copyright deposits,
wouldn't lie.

00:50:44.630 --> 00:50:49.090
And I went looking for
that and I didn't find it.

00:50:49.090 --> 00:50:55.380
But then again, I was trying to get
14,000 pieces of music up online.

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:59.900
So, you know, go ahead,
it's all up there.

00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:04.970
Do us a service and find
it, the Pete Seegre of 1917.

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:09.970
&gt;&gt; I think we have time for
one more question if there is.

00:51:15.890 --> 00:51:17.190
&gt;&gt; All right, well, thank you Paul.

00:51:17.190 --> 00:51:18.490
We really appreciate it.

00:51:18.490 --> 00:51:20.290
&gt;&gt;Paul Fraunfelter: Yeah.

00:51:20.290 --> 00:51:24.860
[ Applause ]

